1
00:00:27,193 --> 00:00:29,320
Masumi.

2
00:00:29,988 --> 00:00:31,281
Stop that.

3
00:00:31,865 --> 00:00:33,950
Don't touch dead things.

4
00:00:50,383 --> 00:00:51,217
Hello.

5
00:00:51,718 --> 00:00:53,887
This is Medical Examiner Japan.

6
00:00:58,266 --> 00:01:00,351
Thank you for coming. It's this way.

7
00:01:00,977 --> 00:01:02,979
Yasuo Izawa, 52-year-old male.

8
00:01:03,063 --> 00:01:04,314
Found lying face up

9
00:01:04,397 --> 00:01:07,358
on this road around 1:00 a.m. today
after being hit by a truck.

10
00:01:07,442 --> 00:01:09,527
A passerby called emergency services.

11
00:01:09,611 --> 00:01:14,032
When they arrived, they concluded
he had already passed away.

12
00:01:14,115 --> 00:01:17,702
That man over there is the first witness,
Nobuhiko Yamanuki.

13
00:01:17,786 --> 00:01:20,705
His company handles transportation
for Mr. Izawa's factory.

14
00:01:20,789 --> 00:01:22,999
At our company,
we're all part of a family…

15
00:01:23,083 --> 00:01:25,919
It seems they were somewhat
acquainted through work.

16
00:01:27,545 --> 00:01:28,588
What?

17
00:01:28,671 --> 00:01:29,798
Doctor?

18
00:01:32,592 --> 00:01:35,011
Is this car paint?

19
00:01:35,094 --> 00:01:36,221
Paint fragments?

20
00:01:37,430 --> 00:01:40,308
The same paint is on him here.

21
00:01:40,391 --> 00:01:42,852
There are broken glass fragments
over here too.

22
00:01:43,978 --> 00:01:46,189
Does this mean he was hit by a car?

23
00:01:46,272 --> 00:01:48,191
- Probably.
- No.

24
00:01:48,274 --> 00:01:50,735
We can't be sure of that yet
with just this.

25
00:01:50,819 --> 00:01:53,238
This is near Mr. Izawa's home.

26
00:01:53,321 --> 00:01:56,407
<i>It's believed he was in an accident</i>
<i>while on his way back.</i>

27
00:01:57,909 --> 00:01:59,494
<i>Were there no witnesses?</i>

28
00:01:59,577 --> 00:02:01,121
None so far.

29
00:02:01,204 --> 00:02:04,165
However,
Mr. Izawa's smartphone is missing.

30
00:02:04,249 --> 00:02:06,876
The perpetrator likely took it.

31
00:02:07,836 --> 00:02:09,921
To prevent him from calling for help?

32
00:02:10,004 --> 00:02:11,089
Presumably.

33
00:02:11,172 --> 00:02:12,507
Presumably.

34
00:02:12,590 --> 00:02:14,801
With the scene in mind,

35
00:02:14,884 --> 00:02:17,262
this doesn't look like
a simple traffic accident.

36
00:02:18,596 --> 00:02:19,722
Doctor?

37
00:02:19,806 --> 00:02:21,099
What is it?

38
00:02:22,475 --> 00:02:25,645
The estimated point of impact
based on the paint fragments,

39
00:02:25,728 --> 00:02:28,565
and Mr. Izawa's position
are too close together.

40
00:02:28,648 --> 00:02:29,983
What do you mean?

41
00:02:30,066 --> 00:02:32,235
In a collision with a vehicle,

42
00:02:32,318 --> 00:02:35,029
a person would normally
be thrown further away.

43
00:02:35,113 --> 00:02:36,906
No matter how small the car is,

44
00:02:36,990 --> 00:02:40,118
you are hitting a mass of steel
weighing over 300 kilograms.

45
00:02:41,035 --> 00:02:41,911
It doesn't add up.

46
00:02:41,995 --> 00:02:43,788
You can't say for certain

47
00:02:43,872 --> 00:02:46,416
that these fragments fell
at the moment of impact.

48
00:02:46,499 --> 00:02:50,753
But you could also say that they did.

49
00:02:50,837 --> 00:02:52,797
In other words, it's a mystery.

50
00:02:54,048 --> 00:02:55,425
There's one more issue.

51
00:02:55,508 --> 00:02:56,801
Huh? What is it?

52
00:02:56,885 --> 00:02:58,428
Acceleration marks.

53
00:03:01,055 --> 00:03:04,183
These are marks left
when a car accelerates.

54
00:03:04,267 --> 00:03:06,144
The presence of acceleration marks

55
00:03:06,227 --> 00:03:09,689
implies the car hit Mr. Izawa
at a high speed.

56
00:03:09,772 --> 00:03:13,276
In that case,
he should have landed further away.

57
00:03:13,359 --> 00:03:16,070
So what's your point?

58
00:03:17,405 --> 00:03:19,949
For now, it's a mystery.

59
00:03:20,700 --> 00:03:22,285
- So--
- All right, all right.

60
00:03:22,368 --> 00:03:24,245
I get it, I get it.

61
00:03:40,470 --> 00:03:41,679
Let's begin.

62
00:03:51,689 --> 00:03:55,818
There are signs of bruising
on the back of the head and shoulders.

63
00:03:55,902 --> 00:03:59,864
But I don't believe
this was the fatal blow.

64
00:03:59,948 --> 00:04:04,786
There are also marks on the thigh
resembling a bumper impact,

65
00:04:04,869 --> 00:04:08,039
but that is also unlikely
to be the cause of death.

66
00:04:08,122 --> 00:04:10,124
Upon opening the retroperitoneum,

67
00:04:10,208 --> 00:04:13,086
the tissue around the pelvis
was found to be completely blackened.

68
00:04:13,169 --> 00:04:18,299
<i>The pelvis was severely fractured,</i>
<i>causing massive internal bleeding.</i>

69
00:04:18,383 --> 00:04:21,886
So the cause of death
was internal bleeding?

70
00:04:21,970 --> 00:04:22,804
Yes.

71
00:04:22,887 --> 00:04:26,057
I believe Mr. Izawa's cause of death
was hemorrhagic shock

72
00:04:26,140 --> 00:04:28,017
due to a pelvic fracture.

73
00:04:28,101 --> 00:04:31,437
Well, at least it seems certain
it was a traffic accident.

74
00:04:31,521 --> 00:04:35,066
In a traffic accident,
a person reflexively tries

75
00:04:35,149 --> 00:04:37,902
to protect their body with their arms
at the moment of impact.

76
00:04:37,986 --> 00:04:42,532
Naturally, defense wounds
would remain on one of the arms.

77
00:04:42,615 --> 00:04:44,617
However, in Mr. Izawa's case,

78
00:04:44,701 --> 00:04:46,661
there are none.

79
00:04:46,744 --> 00:04:47,954
It doesn't add up.

80
00:04:48,037 --> 00:04:50,248
That is certainly unnatural.

81
00:04:50,331 --> 00:04:52,750
There are not enough injuries
for a collision.

82
00:04:52,834 --> 00:04:55,211
Usually, there are skin tears.

83
00:04:55,295 --> 00:04:56,629
And yet,

84
00:04:56,713 --> 00:04:59,257
there's only one cut
on the back of his hand.

85
00:04:59,340 --> 00:05:00,591
You're right.

86
00:05:03,052 --> 00:05:06,097
The pieces of the puzzle
may be coming together.

87
00:05:07,140 --> 00:05:11,269
If Mr. Izawa's death
was caused by a car collision,

88
00:05:11,352 --> 00:05:13,813
and the pelvic fracture…

89
00:05:14,647 --> 00:05:18,151
Then he must have been hit
by a car moving extremely slowly.

90
00:05:18,234 --> 00:05:20,361
For now, it's a mystery.

91
00:05:20,445 --> 00:05:21,487
- What?
- What?

92
00:05:21,571 --> 00:05:24,115
- What do you mean?
- What do you mean?

93
00:05:24,198 --> 00:05:25,283
Come back…

94
00:05:25,366 --> 00:05:26,743
Yes, excuse me.

95
00:05:27,327 --> 00:05:29,037
Your turn, Dr. Takamori.

96
00:05:29,620 --> 00:05:30,455
Okay.

97
00:05:32,582 --> 00:05:33,541
First,

98
00:05:33,624 --> 00:05:36,419
when hit by a fast car,

99
00:05:36,502 --> 00:05:40,715
you are thrown a significant distance
and suffer various external injuries.

100
00:05:41,632 --> 00:05:45,011
But if hit by a very slow car,

101
00:05:45,094 --> 00:05:46,971
you fall straight backward.

102
00:05:47,472 --> 00:05:49,265
Like a heavy fall on your rear.

103
00:05:49,932 --> 00:05:52,894
In this case, the force is focused
on the center of the body,

104
00:05:52,977 --> 00:05:54,729
which can cause a pelvic fracture.

105
00:05:54,812 --> 00:05:57,982
I see. That would explain
why there are external injuries,

106
00:05:58,066 --> 00:06:00,443
but a severe internal one.

107
00:06:00,526 --> 00:06:01,611
Hang on a second.

108
00:06:02,361 --> 00:06:04,781
How slow is "slow"?

109
00:06:08,826 --> 00:06:10,286
About 20 kilometers per hour?

110
00:06:10,369 --> 00:06:13,956
You can easily avoid a car
moving that slowly, can't you?

111
00:06:14,040 --> 00:06:17,168
At the very least,
it wouldn't be a direct hit.

112
00:06:17,251 --> 00:06:19,128
Then maybe he was hit intentionally?

113
00:06:19,212 --> 00:06:21,631
Don't you think that's a bit of a stretch?

114
00:06:21,714 --> 00:06:22,924
That's right!

115
00:06:24,383 --> 00:06:26,928
Doctor, what do you think?

116
00:06:27,637 --> 00:06:28,471
Well…

117
00:06:31,140 --> 00:06:33,726
If the vehicle was moving fast,

118
00:06:33,810 --> 00:06:35,853
<i>it contradicts the body's distance.</i>

119
00:06:35,937 --> 00:06:38,189
<i>If the vehicle was moving slowly,</i>

120
00:06:38,272 --> 00:06:41,192
<i>there should not be</i>
<i>any acceleration marks.</i>

121
00:06:41,275 --> 00:06:45,113
Several points don't add up,
whether it moved slowly or fast.

122
00:06:45,196 --> 00:06:48,783
<i>And, the lack of defense wounds</i>
<i>remains unexplained.</i>

123
00:06:48,866 --> 00:06:50,952
Considering all of this…

124
00:06:53,287 --> 00:06:54,622
Considering all of that?

125
00:06:57,333 --> 00:06:59,502
For now, it's a mystery.

126
00:07:17,186 --> 00:07:18,020
Yes?

127
00:07:20,606 --> 00:07:21,441
What?

128
00:07:24,902 --> 00:07:26,279
I understand.

129
00:07:28,406 --> 00:07:29,490
Was that Dojima?

130
00:07:30,199 --> 00:07:31,033
Yes.

131
00:07:31,117 --> 00:07:32,952
It seems they found the truck driver.

132
00:07:33,035 --> 00:07:35,037
I would like to hear what he has to say.

133
00:07:35,121 --> 00:07:36,247
Wait, Doctor…

134
00:07:37,165 --> 00:07:39,167
Well, about that…

135
00:07:47,884 --> 00:07:50,428
The deceased is Kazutoshi Tamura,
24 years old.

136
00:07:50,511 --> 00:07:53,055
He was the driver
of the truck in the incident.

137
00:07:53,139 --> 00:07:56,309
A missing person's report
was filed by his transport company.

138
00:07:56,392 --> 00:07:59,854
We confirmed he was using the truck
on the day of the incident.

139
00:08:03,024 --> 00:08:04,859
Anything catch your eye?

140
00:08:06,527 --> 00:08:07,528
Where's the truck?

141
00:08:07,612 --> 00:08:09,906
It was abandoned nearby.

142
00:08:14,785 --> 00:08:17,413
The bumper is dented,
and the paint is chipped.

143
00:08:19,624 --> 00:08:23,127
Mr. Izawa's smartphone
was found in the deceased's pocket.

144
00:08:23,211 --> 00:08:24,253
What?

145
00:08:24,337 --> 00:08:25,963
And on top of that.

146
00:08:28,341 --> 00:08:30,968
This was found in his pocket as well.

147
00:08:31,052 --> 00:08:32,220
The police think

148
00:08:32,303 --> 00:08:35,389
it was a suicide motivated
by remorse over the hit-and-run.

149
00:08:40,895 --> 00:08:44,232
The driver suspected of the hit-and-run

150
00:08:44,899 --> 00:08:47,443
was found dead by hanging.

151
00:08:52,865 --> 00:08:54,909
So he killed my husband

152
00:08:56,410 --> 00:08:59,080
and then just took
the easy way out for himself?

153
00:09:02,041 --> 00:09:03,918
How could this happen?

154
00:09:06,963 --> 00:09:09,924
I understand how you feel.

155
00:09:13,511 --> 00:09:18,641
Do you recognize this man named Tamura?

156
00:09:19,809 --> 00:09:22,228
Anything at all will help.

157
00:09:24,438 --> 00:09:28,734
He has come to our factory a few times.

158
00:09:30,444 --> 00:09:33,447
I think he was in charge
of our deliveries.

159
00:09:35,074 --> 00:09:39,495
Did you notice anything
strange about their relationship?

160
00:09:41,414 --> 00:09:42,498
One time,

161
00:09:42,582 --> 00:09:46,877
<i>I saw the two of them having an argument.</i>

162
00:09:47,503 --> 00:09:50,756
Do you know what it was about?

163
00:09:52,008 --> 00:09:54,635
I couldn't hear any details.

164
00:09:54,719 --> 00:09:59,473
When I asked my husband
if he was all right,

165
00:10:00,099 --> 00:10:02,226
I got no clear answer.

166
00:10:03,185 --> 00:10:07,231
Would you say they were
on bad terms with each other?

167
00:10:08,816 --> 00:10:09,859
No.

168
00:10:09,942 --> 00:10:11,360
I don't think they were.

169
00:10:13,279 --> 00:10:17,074
Did they often meet with each other?

170
00:10:20,411 --> 00:10:22,872
I don't know any details, but…

171
00:10:23,581 --> 00:10:27,293
I think they met a few times every month.

172
00:10:29,837 --> 00:10:31,964
Thank you.

173
00:10:37,428 --> 00:10:39,305
<i>He hits him with his truck,</i>

174
00:10:39,388 --> 00:10:41,932
and then commits suicide over the guilt.

175
00:10:42,516 --> 00:10:44,018
That's the size of it, right?

176
00:10:44,101 --> 00:10:46,687
We don't currently know.

177
00:10:47,396 --> 00:10:51,233
If they had some bad blood
between each other for whatever reason,

178
00:10:51,317 --> 00:10:54,695
then it's a possibility he hit him
with his truck on purpose, isn't it?

179
00:10:55,529 --> 00:10:59,367
We don't currently know that either.

180
00:11:00,451 --> 00:11:02,078
You're right.

181
00:11:02,828 --> 00:11:03,913
Sorry.

182
00:11:04,538 --> 00:11:07,208
However,
there is one thing that caught my eye.

183
00:11:08,167 --> 00:11:09,001
What is it?

184
00:11:09,085 --> 00:11:12,380
The condition of Tamura's body
at the scene.

185
00:11:12,463 --> 00:11:15,299
Normally, when one dies
from asphyxiation from hanging,

186
00:11:15,383 --> 00:11:17,385
their face becomes pale.

187
00:11:17,468 --> 00:11:21,514
<i>However, Tamura's complexion</i>
<i>looked just fine.</i>

188
00:11:21,597 --> 00:11:24,141
He had all the color in his face, right?

189
00:11:24,225 --> 00:11:25,309
Yes.

190
00:11:25,893 --> 00:11:26,811
Therefore…

191
00:11:33,734 --> 00:11:34,777
Let's begin.

192
00:11:43,702 --> 00:11:44,870
It's over here!

193
00:11:46,372 --> 00:11:49,125
YAMANUKI SHIPPING CO., LTD.

194
00:11:49,208 --> 00:11:54,004
Could you tell us about
how Kazutoshi Tamura was at work?

195
00:11:54,588 --> 00:11:55,714
Right…

196
00:11:55,798 --> 00:11:57,133
Tamura…

197
00:11:59,135 --> 00:12:03,055
It honestly pains me
to speak ill of the dead.

198
00:12:03,139 --> 00:12:04,974
Were there any problems?

199
00:12:06,183 --> 00:12:09,228
<i>He was often found sleeping</i>
<i>in the middle of work.</i>

200
00:12:09,311 --> 00:12:10,646
Are you okay?

201
00:12:11,272 --> 00:12:12,189
Sorry.

202
00:12:12,815 --> 00:12:14,442
He was not very bright.

203
00:12:17,111 --> 00:12:18,237
What are you doing?

204
00:12:18,320 --> 00:12:21,490
<i>To be honest,</i>
<i>I wasn't sure what to do about him.</i>

205
00:12:23,784 --> 00:12:25,578
I didn't really want to do this,

206
00:12:25,661 --> 00:12:28,205
but I attached a GPS to his truck
to monitor him.

207
00:12:28,289 --> 00:12:30,082
A GPS…

208
00:12:30,166 --> 00:12:33,252
We also have the shift records over there.

209
00:12:33,335 --> 00:12:36,130
- Please look at them if needed.
- Thank you very much.

210
00:12:45,514 --> 00:12:46,348
Hey.

211
00:12:46,432 --> 00:12:47,475
Yes, sorry!

212
00:12:52,271 --> 00:12:55,816
There was mild pulmonary edema
in his lungs.

213
00:12:56,734 --> 00:12:59,528
This can be a sign of asphyxiation,

214
00:12:59,612 --> 00:13:03,115
but also a sign of heart failure
or death from poisoning.

215
00:13:03,199 --> 00:13:04,825
The CT scan results show

216
00:13:04,909 --> 00:13:07,244
that the decisive blow
wasn't to the heart or brain.

217
00:13:07,328 --> 00:13:08,913
It doesn't seem like heart failure.

218
00:13:08,996 --> 00:13:10,331
Thank you.

219
00:13:10,998 --> 00:13:12,833
Next, on the neck,

220
00:13:12,917 --> 00:13:16,295
there are clear rope marks left.

221
00:13:16,378 --> 00:13:18,464
So, he died by hanging?

222
00:13:18,547 --> 00:13:21,425
We can't draw a conclusion just from that.

223
00:13:21,509 --> 00:13:23,594
Because you can make it look like

224
00:13:23,677 --> 00:13:26,305
someone hanged themselves
after killing them, right?

225
00:13:26,388 --> 00:13:27,515
Yes.

226
00:13:27,598 --> 00:13:31,810
There is one more thing
that caught my eye during the autopsy.

227
00:13:32,478 --> 00:13:33,938
<i>Thank you for your cooperation.</i>

228
00:13:34,021 --> 00:13:35,898
No, I'm happy to help with this.

229
00:13:35,981 --> 00:13:37,399
Well then, goodbye.

230
00:13:38,108 --> 00:13:39,652
By the way…

231
00:13:41,487 --> 00:13:45,074
you wouldn't know about any trouble
Izawa was having, would you?

232
00:13:45,157 --> 00:13:46,575
Trouble?

233
00:13:47,368 --> 00:13:49,119
Trouble…

234
00:13:49,203 --> 00:13:50,079
Well…

235
00:13:50,162 --> 00:13:51,372
Did you think of something?

236
00:13:51,455 --> 00:13:53,290
Well, it's only a rumor.

237
00:13:53,374 --> 00:13:55,125
Only a rumor?

238
00:13:55,209 --> 00:13:56,627
Actually…

239
00:13:59,463 --> 00:14:00,714
Take a look at this.

240
00:14:01,507 --> 00:14:04,176
There are few petechial hemorrhages
behind the eyes.

241
00:14:04,260 --> 00:14:05,886
<i>In cases of asphyxiation,</i>

242
00:14:05,970 --> 00:14:09,014
<i>blood that should flow down</i>
<i>from the neck pools,</i>

243
00:14:09,098 --> 00:14:12,101
<i>and there should be</i>
<i>signs of bleeding behind the eyes.</i>

244
00:14:12,184 --> 00:14:14,770
If it wasn't hanging, then what was it?

245
00:14:15,396 --> 00:14:18,148
We're still missing some pieces.

246
00:14:19,900 --> 00:14:21,986
How was the autopsy for Kazutoshi Tamura?

247
00:14:22,069 --> 00:14:23,320
How was it?

248
00:14:23,404 --> 00:14:26,532
We couldn't conclude
that Tamura's cause of death was hanging.

249
00:14:26,615 --> 00:14:27,783
I see.

250
00:14:27,867 --> 00:14:29,076
What about you?

251
00:14:30,077 --> 00:14:31,662
We learned something interesting.

252
00:14:32,997 --> 00:14:37,543
Izawa had been in debt
for two years to run the factory.

253
00:14:37,626 --> 00:14:39,336
Nearly 100 million yen.

254
00:14:39,420 --> 00:14:40,838
What? 100 million?

255
00:14:40,921 --> 00:14:41,922
That's not all.

256
00:14:42,006 --> 00:14:45,342
A 100 million yen life insurance policy
was taken out on Izawa.

257
00:14:45,426 --> 00:14:48,596
And it's only been three months
since he signed it.

258
00:14:48,679 --> 00:14:51,307
I see it as money to protect the company.

259
00:14:51,390 --> 00:14:55,185
The police are moving forward with
the investigation as a case

260
00:14:55,269 --> 00:14:57,187
<i>of induced suicide by Akemi Izawa.</i>

261
00:14:57,688 --> 00:15:00,441
Wait, what does that mean?

262
00:15:01,400 --> 00:15:04,987
We mean that she induced Izawa
to commit suicide

263
00:15:05,070 --> 00:15:07,364
and make it look like an accident.

264
00:15:07,448 --> 00:15:10,242
To get the 100 million
from the life insurance policy.

265
00:15:10,326 --> 00:15:11,702
No, wait.

266
00:15:12,411 --> 00:15:13,454
If that's true,

267
00:15:13,537 --> 00:15:17,541
then why would the driver,
Tamura, have to die?

268
00:15:18,250 --> 00:15:22,671
If it's discovered he committed suicide,
then she won't get the 100 million.

269
00:15:22,755 --> 00:15:25,049
<i>She killed the driver, Kazutoshi Tamura,</i>

270
00:15:25,132 --> 00:15:28,052
<i>and made it look like a suicide.</i>

271
00:15:29,219 --> 00:15:32,348
Then it would make sense
that he didn't have much hemorrhaging

272
00:15:32,431 --> 00:15:35,142
because he didn't die of asphyxiation.

273
00:15:35,225 --> 00:15:39,605
That may also explain why Izawa
didn't dodge a slow-moving truck.

274
00:15:39,688 --> 00:15:41,982
<i>Because she hesitated</i>
<i>to run over her husband,</i>

275
00:15:42,066 --> 00:15:44,318
<i>Akemi hit Mr. Izawa</i>
<i>at a half-hearted speed.</i>

276
00:15:45,152 --> 00:15:47,488
Does that mean Akemi is the culprit?

277
00:15:47,571 --> 00:15:49,782
We'll go ask the suspect directly.

278
00:15:49,865 --> 00:15:52,451
Yes. We'll check with the insurance
company for--

279
00:15:52,534 --> 00:15:53,494
Don't dawdle!

280
00:15:53,577 --> 00:15:54,703
Yes, ma'am!

281
00:15:54,787 --> 00:15:56,163
I'll get the referral!

282
00:16:07,341 --> 00:16:08,384
Doctor,

283
00:16:09,093 --> 00:16:10,427
what do you think?

284
00:16:27,528 --> 00:16:29,738
<i>The night of the accident?</i>

285
00:16:29,822 --> 00:16:31,573
I was at home.

286
00:16:32,825 --> 00:16:35,285
I see.

287
00:16:35,953 --> 00:16:39,164
I'm under suspicion, aren't I?

288
00:16:40,124 --> 00:16:42,918
Oh, no, it's nothing like that.

289
00:16:44,253 --> 00:16:46,255
A police officer came by earlier, too,

290
00:16:47,131 --> 00:16:50,009
and asked me all sorts of things.

291
00:16:55,139 --> 00:16:58,517
Like about how managing the factory
wasn't going well,

292
00:16:59,476 --> 00:17:01,812
and about my husband's
life insurance money.

293
00:17:03,063 --> 00:17:08,694
I wonder if they think I killed him
for the insurance money.

294
00:17:09,361 --> 00:17:11,488
No, we're not saying that.

295
00:17:11,572 --> 00:17:14,033
Just because we have debts to pay back…

296
00:17:14,116 --> 00:17:17,661
I haven't fallen so low
as to commit murder.

297
00:17:20,122 --> 00:17:21,540
I'm very sorry.

298
00:17:23,500 --> 00:17:25,502
You have a child, huh?

299
00:17:30,049 --> 00:17:31,258
Yes.

300
00:17:32,092 --> 00:17:32,926
Well…

301
00:17:35,471 --> 00:17:36,722
Kazuki…

302
00:17:38,766 --> 00:17:41,727
passed away ten years ago.

303
00:17:44,980 --> 00:17:46,273
It was suicide.

304
00:17:48,984 --> 00:17:50,152
Kazuki

305
00:17:50,986 --> 00:17:52,112
was a serious boy.

306
00:17:53,322 --> 00:17:55,074
But he was clumsy,

307
00:17:55,157 --> 00:17:57,159
and everything he tried

308
00:17:57,242 --> 00:17:59,578
seemed to go nowhere.

309
00:18:01,330 --> 00:18:04,333
<i>His job hunting didn't go well either.</i>

310
00:18:10,756 --> 00:18:12,091
REJECTION NOTICE

311
00:18:12,174 --> 00:18:13,092
<i>Kazuki.</i>

312
00:18:13,759 --> 00:18:14,802
I'm coming in.

313
00:18:24,937 --> 00:18:26,814
Is it not going well?

314
00:18:29,399 --> 00:18:30,567
Dad, actually…

315
00:18:30,651 --> 00:18:31,527
What?

316
00:18:32,528 --> 00:18:36,323
Would it be okay
if I worked for your company?

317
00:18:38,992 --> 00:18:41,870
Even if you join us, you'll only suffer.

318
00:18:43,288 --> 00:18:45,791
Why don't you keep at it
just a little bit longer?

319
00:18:50,170 --> 00:18:53,674
<i>My husband didn't really want</i>
<i>him to join the company,</i>

320
00:18:55,843 --> 00:18:58,762
but to find a better job,

321
00:18:59,596 --> 00:19:01,974
and become happy.

322
00:19:07,229 --> 00:19:08,397
But that day…

323
00:19:09,022 --> 00:19:10,816
Kazuki, I'm coming in.

324
00:19:11,441 --> 00:19:12,568
I've got breakfast--

325
00:19:15,070 --> 00:19:17,781
<i>It was my husband who found Kazuki</i>

326
00:19:18,949 --> 00:19:20,284
<i>after he had hanged himself.</i>

327
00:19:26,915 --> 00:19:28,959
My husband thought that if only

328
00:19:30,002 --> 00:19:32,963
he had noticed Kazuki's
suffering back then, Kazuki would…

329
00:19:34,339 --> 00:19:37,342
My husband always blamed himself for it.

330
00:19:39,928 --> 00:19:41,013
Day…

331
00:19:43,515 --> 00:19:44,558
after day…

332
00:19:51,273 --> 00:19:54,443
I would never do such a thing.

333
00:20:02,117 --> 00:20:04,077
I don't think it's possible after all.

334
00:20:07,039 --> 00:20:09,917
I don't think someone
who cares so much for their family

335
00:20:10,751 --> 00:20:13,170
would commit instigation of suicide.

336
00:20:15,964 --> 00:20:21,345
You cannot conclude
whether a parent is truly

337
00:20:22,971 --> 00:20:24,556
thinking of their child.

338
00:20:49,831 --> 00:20:53,126
The doctor was kind of strange today.

339
00:20:53,835 --> 00:20:56,171
From what I know, he just seems like that.

340
00:20:57,297 --> 00:20:58,507
Well, yes.

341
00:20:59,216 --> 00:21:01,093
He's always calm and collected, right?

342
00:21:01,176 --> 00:21:02,844
He just does sudoku.

343
00:21:03,512 --> 00:21:04,388
Yeah.

344
00:21:05,097 --> 00:21:05,931
Oh.

345
00:21:06,431 --> 00:21:09,226
Maybe it's just not a topic
he's comfortable with.

346
00:21:10,227 --> 00:21:11,311
Not comfortable?

347
00:21:11,937 --> 00:21:14,690
Like parental love?
It's not that uncommon.

348
00:21:56,356 --> 00:21:59,526
I'm very sorry about the other day…

349
00:22:03,905 --> 00:22:07,993
I visited the factory,
but you weren't there.

350
00:22:08,827 --> 00:22:11,913
I've decided to close down the factory.

351
00:22:14,166 --> 00:22:17,169
The management
wasn't going well to begin with.

352
00:22:18,754 --> 00:22:20,672
And my husband is gone now, too.

353
00:22:34,311 --> 00:22:35,395
Ma'am,

354
00:22:36,480 --> 00:22:38,815
if it's all right with you,

355
00:22:38,899 --> 00:22:41,359
could we investigate inside the house?

356
00:22:43,028 --> 00:22:45,447
We might find some kind of clue.

357
00:22:51,495 --> 00:22:55,707
I want to find out exactly
what happened on the day of the incident.

358
00:22:57,167 --> 00:22:58,627
For your husband's sake.

359
00:23:01,838 --> 00:23:03,840
Above all, for your own sake.

360
00:23:10,972 --> 00:23:13,475
<i>He's coming up from the rear!</i>

361
00:23:13,558 --> 00:23:15,227
Go, go, go!

362
00:23:16,394 --> 00:23:18,021
- All right!
- Wow.

363
00:23:18,105 --> 00:23:19,439
You did it.

364
00:23:19,523 --> 00:23:20,482
What?

365
00:23:20,565 --> 00:23:21,650
Right.

366
00:23:23,652 --> 00:23:25,403
Is there anyone here

367
00:23:25,487 --> 00:23:29,825
who used the same truck
as the late Mr. Tamura?

368
00:23:30,784 --> 00:23:32,327
I have.

369
00:23:32,410 --> 00:23:33,829
- Great!
- Me too.

370
00:23:33,912 --> 00:23:34,788
Great!

371
00:23:35,497 --> 00:23:38,416
Have you felt unwell
in the past few weeks?

372
00:23:39,292 --> 00:23:41,002
Just a little dizzy.

373
00:23:41,086 --> 00:23:42,796
I had a cold.

374
00:23:44,381 --> 00:23:45,841
Thank you very much.

375
00:23:45,924 --> 00:23:48,677
There is something I would like to check.

376
00:23:49,928 --> 00:23:52,931
This is the truck
he was driving that night.

377
00:23:53,014 --> 00:23:54,349
Oh, I see.

378
00:23:58,395 --> 00:24:00,313
Oh, may I borrow this?

379
00:24:04,442 --> 00:24:06,903
Hey… Are you okay?

380
00:24:06,987 --> 00:24:09,114
Oh, don't worry.

381
00:24:17,205 --> 00:24:19,374
I'm sorry to be so forward.

382
00:24:19,457 --> 00:24:21,084
No…

383
00:24:27,591 --> 00:24:29,885
If I take anything that seems of interest,

384
00:24:29,968 --> 00:24:31,928
even if I don't understand what it is,

385
00:24:32,554 --> 00:24:35,390
Dr. Masumi might notice something.

386
00:24:38,894 --> 00:24:40,520
Well, in that case,

387
00:24:41,271 --> 00:24:44,482
would you like to check Kazuki's room too?

388
00:24:45,108 --> 00:24:46,193
What?

389
00:24:50,822 --> 00:24:51,990
This is it.

390
00:24:54,993 --> 00:24:59,497
We've left it just as it was
since Kazuki passed.

391
00:25:01,333 --> 00:25:02,792
Neither I nor my husband

392
00:25:03,460 --> 00:25:05,462
could quite accept it.

393
00:25:11,009 --> 00:25:12,427
If you would like,

394
00:25:13,595 --> 00:25:15,513
could you investigate it?

395
00:25:17,057 --> 00:25:17,891
Yes.

396
00:25:20,310 --> 00:25:21,603
Thank you very much.

397
00:25:24,272 --> 00:25:25,148
I'll go in then.

398
00:25:43,041 --> 00:25:45,043
I used to have one of these, too.

399
00:25:46,044 --> 00:25:48,922
When I first started working,
I tried to act like an adult.

400
00:25:51,299 --> 00:25:53,176
That fountain pen

401
00:25:53,927 --> 00:25:56,846
is something my husband
gave to Kazuki as a present.

402
00:25:57,847 --> 00:26:00,433
When his job hunting wasn't going well,

403
00:26:00,517 --> 00:26:02,936
he told him that if he used it
to write his resumes,

404
00:26:03,019 --> 00:26:04,187
he would be fine.

405
00:26:17,367 --> 00:26:18,535
I'm back!

406
00:26:18,618 --> 00:26:20,036
Ms. Kiryu, what's all that?

407
00:26:20,120 --> 00:26:22,205
I got permission from Akemi

408
00:26:22,289 --> 00:26:24,249
and borrowed some of his belongings.

409
00:26:24,332 --> 00:26:25,458
This much?

410
00:26:25,542 --> 00:26:26,418
Yes.

411
00:26:28,044 --> 00:26:28,962
Everyone.

412
00:26:29,045 --> 00:26:31,298
Could you help me investigate everything?

413
00:26:31,381 --> 00:26:33,341
How are we going to handle all this?

414
00:26:33,425 --> 00:26:35,927
I'm busy too, you know. I'll pass.

415
00:26:36,011 --> 00:26:37,053
Please.

416
00:26:37,679 --> 00:26:38,972
I'm asking you.

417
00:26:41,683 --> 00:26:43,435
Dr. Masumi, you too, please.

418
00:26:46,896 --> 00:26:49,691
I just can't believe Akemi is the culprit.

419
00:26:50,317 --> 00:26:54,404
So, I thought you might be able
to find some kind of clue.

420
00:26:56,489 --> 00:26:57,574
Please.

421
00:26:58,408 --> 00:26:59,659
Of course.

422
00:27:00,285 --> 00:27:01,578
Thank you very much.

423
00:27:02,579 --> 00:27:03,621
All right.

424
00:27:05,165 --> 00:27:07,250
You too, Dr. Matsubara.

425
00:27:07,334 --> 00:27:08,835
- Ugh.
- Come on.

426
00:27:08,918 --> 00:27:11,087
I've got a show I want to watch!

427
00:27:11,171 --> 00:27:12,922
Just record it, then.

428
00:27:14,507 --> 00:27:15,759
Here, thank you.

429
00:27:18,678 --> 00:27:19,512
All right.

430
00:27:24,225 --> 00:27:25,101
Hey.

431
00:27:25,894 --> 00:27:30,273
This is a gift Izawa gave to Kazuki
when he was job hunting.

432
00:27:38,198 --> 00:27:40,450
- What were Tamura's blood test results?
- Hold on.

433
00:27:40,950 --> 00:27:41,910
Where are they…

434
00:27:43,703 --> 00:27:44,746
Here.

435
00:27:46,498 --> 00:27:47,957
Acetaminophen.

436
00:27:50,794 --> 00:27:52,545
What is that?

437
00:27:53,546 --> 00:27:56,466
It's an ingredient often found
in things like cold medicine.

438
00:28:06,935 --> 00:28:08,311
<i>You can make it look like</i>

439
00:28:08,395 --> 00:28:09,979
<i>someone hanged themselves…</i>

440
00:28:10,063 --> 00:28:11,356
<i>…no defense wounds.</i>

441
00:28:11,439 --> 00:28:13,149
<i>There's only one cut</i>
<i>on the back of his hand.</i>

442
00:28:13,233 --> 00:28:14,442
Just a little dizzy.

443
00:28:14,526 --> 00:28:15,860
I had a cold.

444
00:28:15,944 --> 00:28:18,696
<i>Kazuki passed away ten years ago.</i>

445
00:28:18,780 --> 00:28:21,741
<i>This is a gift Izawa gave to Kazuki</i>
<i>when he was job hunting.</i>

446
00:28:21,825 --> 00:28:23,451
<i>Acetaminophen.</i>

447
00:28:23,535 --> 00:28:26,246
I think they met a few times every month.

448
00:28:41,720 --> 00:28:43,263
The pieces may be

449
00:28:45,181 --> 00:28:47,225
coming together.

450
00:29:03,992 --> 00:29:06,745
MUSASHINODAI POLICE OFFICE

451
00:29:14,461 --> 00:29:17,672
Thank you for coming while you're so busy.

452
00:29:17,756 --> 00:29:20,842
There is something
I would like to ask you about.

453
00:29:21,342 --> 00:29:23,595
I'm sorry, but I'm busy,

454
00:29:23,678 --> 00:29:26,055
so could we finish this
as quickly as possible?

455
00:29:27,098 --> 00:29:28,099
I understand.

456
00:29:36,274 --> 00:29:37,108
Right this way.

457
00:29:40,445 --> 00:29:41,613
Please, have a seat here.

458
00:29:41,696 --> 00:29:42,530
Okay.

459
00:29:45,700 --> 00:29:51,164
These are photos taken
when I visited your company the other day.

460
00:29:53,625 --> 00:29:55,627
You can't just take liberties like that.

461
00:29:55,710 --> 00:29:57,378
I'm terribly sorry.

462
00:29:58,046 --> 00:30:01,508
I just had something
that was bothering me.

463
00:30:04,594 --> 00:30:07,597
This is the truck Tamura
drove on the night of the incident.

464
00:30:07,680 --> 00:30:09,265
Please look at this part.

465
00:30:09,349 --> 00:30:10,975
The pipe is broken.

466
00:30:11,726 --> 00:30:16,189
Also, there are cracks in the welding
several centimeters big.

467
00:30:18,316 --> 00:30:21,277
And there is one more thing
that concerns me.

468
00:30:24,280 --> 00:30:27,700
Tamura had been suffering from symptoms

469
00:30:27,784 --> 00:30:31,079
like dizziness and a cold
for several weeks.

470
00:30:31,162 --> 00:30:32,539
Strangely,

471
00:30:33,206 --> 00:30:38,336
there were several others
suffering from similar symptoms.

472
00:30:38,419 --> 00:30:40,338
It's just a coincidence.

473
00:30:40,421 --> 00:30:42,632
Everyone at our company works hard,

474
00:30:42,715 --> 00:30:45,218
so it wouldn't be strange
for them to fall ill.

475
00:30:46,636 --> 00:30:50,849
I do not believe
that it was a coincidence.

476
00:30:52,475 --> 00:30:54,018
On what grounds?

477
00:30:54,602 --> 00:30:56,229
I believe the workers

478
00:30:56,312 --> 00:31:01,192
were suffering from
carbon monoxide poisoning.

479
00:31:03,361 --> 00:31:05,405
On the day of the incident,

480
00:31:05,488 --> 00:31:07,490
<i>Tamura parked the truck on the street,</i>

481
00:31:07,574 --> 00:31:11,411
<i>and exhausted from working all day,</i>
<i>took a nap.</i>

482
00:31:12,912 --> 00:31:14,038
That day,

483
00:31:14,122 --> 00:31:16,624
it was very humid,
even when the sun went down.

484
00:31:17,876 --> 00:31:21,588
<i>He most likely left the air conditioner on</i>
<i>while inside the vehicle.</i>

485
00:31:22,922 --> 00:31:26,593
<i>If you continue to run it</i>
<i>while parked for a long time,</i>

486
00:31:27,385 --> 00:31:32,724
<i>exhaust gas will begin to accumulate</i>
<i>under the vehicle from that broken pipe.</i>

487
00:31:33,766 --> 00:31:35,268
<i>As a result,</i>

488
00:31:35,351 --> 00:31:37,604
<i>carbon monoxide,</i>
<i>which is lighter than air,</i>

489
00:31:37,687 --> 00:31:42,650
<i>leaked through the crack</i>
<i>in the bottom of the vehicle.</i>

490
00:31:44,152 --> 00:31:47,697
Tamura, who was sleep-deprived,
had fallen into a deep sleep.

491
00:31:47,780 --> 00:31:51,367
And without even realizing it himself,

492
00:31:51,868 --> 00:31:54,787
he was suffering
from carbon monoxide poisoning.

493
00:31:55,830 --> 00:32:00,585
The reason his complexion looked normal
when his body was found

494
00:32:00,668 --> 00:32:02,295
was because of that.

495
00:32:04,464 --> 00:32:07,592
But what was more decisive than anything…

496
00:32:09,677 --> 00:32:10,762
was this.

497
00:32:12,764 --> 00:32:14,349
I'M SORRY FOR BEING LIKE THIS

498
00:32:15,308 --> 00:32:19,228
This note,
found at the scene of the incident.

499
00:32:20,647 --> 00:32:22,023
And that alone

500
00:32:23,816 --> 00:32:25,318
doesn't add up.

501
00:32:25,401 --> 00:32:26,527
What?

502
00:32:27,278 --> 00:32:28,529
Why?

503
00:32:31,032 --> 00:32:35,954
Initially, we thought this note
was a suicide note left by the driver,

504
00:32:36,037 --> 00:32:37,664
Kazutoshi Tamura.

505
00:32:39,832 --> 00:32:41,209
But we were wrong.

506
00:32:43,127 --> 00:32:45,046
What do you mean?

507
00:32:47,090 --> 00:32:49,384
It was written by your late son.

508
00:32:51,636 --> 00:32:52,804
What…

509
00:32:53,721 --> 00:32:58,309
These letters haven't bled
through to the back of the paper.

510
00:32:59,227 --> 00:33:03,272
The ink has not been absorbed
into the paper.

511
00:33:03,982 --> 00:33:05,775
If it were oil-based,
it would bleed through.

512
00:33:06,275 --> 00:33:09,862
If it were water-based,
it should smudge because of the paper.

513
00:33:10,405 --> 00:33:12,782
But it is neither of those.

514
00:33:13,408 --> 00:33:17,412
Pigmented gel ink is what it's called.

515
00:33:17,495 --> 00:33:20,039
Pigmented gel ink?

516
00:33:20,123 --> 00:33:26,170
Can you see the fine cracks in the ink
on the surface of these letters?

517
00:33:26,671 --> 00:33:30,174
A characteristic of pigmented gel ink
is that it cracks

518
00:33:30,258 --> 00:33:33,219
after several years of exposure to air.

519
00:33:33,720 --> 00:33:36,097
<i>In other words, that means</i>

520
00:33:36,180 --> 00:33:41,227
this note was written several years ago.

521
00:33:43,146 --> 00:33:44,772
And this ink

522
00:33:44,856 --> 00:33:46,482
matches the fountain pen

523
00:33:46,566 --> 00:33:51,446
that Izawa's son, Kazuki, used to love.

524
00:33:53,364 --> 00:33:55,992
I believe your husband
kept it with him at all times

525
00:33:56,701 --> 00:34:00,496
<i>as a form of atonement.</i>

526
00:34:04,584 --> 00:34:06,586
Why would something Kazuki wrote

527
00:34:07,253 --> 00:34:08,963
be inside the truck?

528
00:34:09,881 --> 00:34:11,174
I believe…

529
00:34:13,051 --> 00:34:15,762
your husband was trying to help Tamura.

530
00:34:20,725 --> 00:34:23,644
<i>That night, when Izawa was going home…</i>

531
00:34:24,479 --> 00:34:25,438
Hey!

532
00:34:25,521 --> 00:34:27,023
Are you sleeping?

533
00:34:27,940 --> 00:34:30,026
You'll catch a cold!

534
00:34:31,319 --> 00:34:32,153
Hey!

535
00:34:32,236 --> 00:34:34,822
Hey, are you okay? Hey!

536
00:34:49,504 --> 00:34:50,880
Hey, what's wrong?

537
00:34:50,963 --> 00:34:53,299
Hey! Pull yourself together!

538
00:34:53,382 --> 00:34:55,426
Hey!

539
00:34:56,427 --> 00:34:57,261
Hey…

540
00:34:57,345 --> 00:34:58,262
All right…

541
00:34:59,764 --> 00:35:04,560
<i>Izawa inhaled carbon monoxide</i>
<i>from the vehicle.</i>

542
00:35:12,235 --> 00:35:15,279
Is that bastard
seriously slacking off again?

543
00:35:27,875 --> 00:35:28,751
Hey!

544
00:35:29,710 --> 00:35:30,878
What happened?

545
00:35:34,507 --> 00:35:35,675
The truck…

546
00:35:37,135 --> 00:35:38,719
Something's wrong with it.

547
00:35:38,803 --> 00:35:40,138
What?

548
00:35:40,221 --> 00:35:41,806
I'm so dizzy.

549
00:35:54,694 --> 00:35:55,528
Hey.

550
00:35:56,445 --> 00:35:57,446
Are you okay?

551
00:35:58,698 --> 00:36:00,825
If this gets out, my company is ruined.

552
00:36:01,617 --> 00:36:03,119
Hey…

553
00:36:04,120 --> 00:36:05,246
Are you okay?

554
00:36:06,080 --> 00:36:07,039
Can you stand?

555
00:36:07,665 --> 00:36:09,458
I finally climbed my way to the top…

556
00:37:05,890 --> 00:37:08,851
<i>And, after that, Yamanuki…</i>

557
00:37:13,022 --> 00:37:15,274
I'M SORRY FOR BEING LIKE THIS

558
00:37:18,444 --> 00:37:21,656
<i>He was desperately trying</i>
<i>to make it look like an accident.</i>

559
00:37:26,619 --> 00:37:28,412
<i>He put Tamura into the truck,</i>

560
00:37:28,913 --> 00:37:30,081
<i>and fled the scene.</i>

561
00:37:42,885 --> 00:37:45,179
<i>Tamura made it look like</i>
<i>he committed suicide.</i>

562
00:37:48,891 --> 00:37:51,602
Considering the above,

563
00:37:53,271 --> 00:37:57,400
I believe the reason Yasuo Izawa
had no defensive wounds

564
00:37:58,526 --> 00:38:05,533
was that he was trying to protect Tamura,
who was unconscious at the time.

565
00:38:10,037 --> 00:38:13,207
If you had called an ambulance right then,

566
00:38:15,167 --> 00:38:18,879
they would both have survived.

567
00:38:23,551 --> 00:38:24,844
Neither of them…

568
00:38:27,221 --> 00:38:29,307
would have lost their lives.

569
00:38:34,854 --> 00:38:36,897
This is what we believe

570
00:38:38,065 --> 00:38:42,361
to have happened to Yasuo Izawa
on that day.

571
00:38:48,868 --> 00:38:49,994
My husband…

572
00:38:52,246 --> 00:38:55,583
tried to save someone?

573
00:38:58,711 --> 00:38:59,670
Yes.

574
00:39:03,299 --> 00:39:07,136
He tried to save Tamura,
who was about the same age as your son.

575
00:39:09,597 --> 00:39:11,307
He risked his life to do it.

576
00:39:28,032 --> 00:39:29,367
I…

577
00:39:31,285 --> 00:39:33,287
think he was a magnificent person.

578
00:39:46,050 --> 00:39:48,928
Detective! Please listen to me!
This man is--

579
00:39:49,011 --> 00:39:53,099
Overworking employees,
false statements, tampering with evidence…

580
00:39:53,182 --> 00:39:55,851
Plus a whole bunch of further offenses.

581
00:39:57,520 --> 00:40:00,272
Nobuhiko Yamanuki, you are under arrest

582
00:40:00,356 --> 00:40:02,608
for murder and failure to render aid.

583
00:40:04,944 --> 00:40:06,070
It looks like

584
00:40:06,153 --> 00:40:09,907
you're going to spend a lot of time
with us, don't you think?

585
00:40:11,742 --> 00:40:12,827
Let's go.

586
00:40:16,789 --> 00:40:17,748
Move!

587
00:40:18,416 --> 00:40:21,919
Thank you for your cooperation.

588
00:40:23,712 --> 00:40:25,005
You as well.

589
00:40:31,345 --> 00:40:32,430
Thank you,

590
00:40:33,180 --> 00:40:34,473
as always.

591
00:40:40,312 --> 00:40:41,480
From here on,

592
00:40:42,773 --> 00:40:44,650
it's police business, so…

593
00:41:02,251 --> 00:41:05,963
IZAWA

594
00:42:00,726 --> 00:42:05,105
I hope Izawa's feelings reached those two.

595
00:42:08,234 --> 00:42:12,029
Oh. From a forensic science
perspective, the deceased are…

596
00:42:12,112 --> 00:42:13,906
Yes, I get it.

597
00:42:21,956 --> 00:42:23,749
Thank you for today.

598
00:42:23,832 --> 00:42:25,125
Good work.

599
00:42:27,711 --> 00:42:29,046
Wait, Doctor.

600
00:42:29,129 --> 00:42:32,174
That reminds me.
I've actually wanted to ask you…

601
00:42:32,258 --> 00:42:35,594
Why did you want to become
a forensic pathologist?

602
00:42:37,680 --> 00:42:40,558
Well, I wonder why.

603
00:42:40,641 --> 00:42:43,143
For now, it's a mystery.

604
00:42:47,273 --> 00:42:48,732
Good work today.

605
00:43:02,329 --> 00:43:03,289
<i>Masumi.</i>

606
00:43:04,790 --> 00:43:06,083
Stop that.

607
00:43:07,042 --> 00:43:08,752
Don't touch dead things.

608
00:43:13,465 --> 00:43:14,633
Why…

609
00:43:17,845 --> 00:43:19,054
Dad?

610
00:43:19,680 --> 00:43:21,348
KOICHI MIZUSAWA

611
00:43:22,891 --> 00:43:24,435
<i>There is no value</i>

612
00:43:25,227 --> 00:43:26,353
in dead things.

613
00:43:40,326 --> 00:43:43,662
THIRD KILLING BY STRANGULATION THIS YEAR

614
00:43:44,496 --> 00:43:47,541
4TH CASE OF WOMAN FOUND STRANGLED

615
00:43:47,625 --> 00:43:50,919
SHIRAMINE SERIAL FEMICIDE CASE
RESEARCH DATA

616
00:43:53,297 --> 00:43:56,258
AUTOPSY REPORT

617
00:43:56,342 --> 00:43:59,678
SURGEON: MASAHITO KUJO
MARCH 2008

618
00:44:01,055 --> 00:44:04,141
ASSISTANT: MASUMI MIZUSAWA

619
00:44:04,224 --> 00:44:06,477
MASUMI MIZUSAWA

620
00:44:17,446 --> 00:44:20,866
Subtitle translation by: Maslin F.
